1. Correlation: Closing Price vs PE Ratio & Dividend Yield by Sector¶

In [7]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Calculate correlations and fix column names
sector_corr = (
    df.groupby('Sector')[['Close', 'PE_Ratio', 'Dividend_Yield']]
    .corr().unstack()
    .loc[:, ('Close', ['PE_Ratio', 'Dividend_Yield'])]  # Select MultiIndex columns
    .reset_index()
)
# Flatten MultiIndex column names and rename
sector_corr.columns = ['Sector', 'PE Ratio', 'Dividend Yield']

# Plot using corrected DataFrame
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))
bar_width = 0.35
x = range(len(sector_corr['Sector']))

ax.bar(x, sector_corr['PE Ratio'], width=bar_width, label='PE Ratio', color='#1f77b4')
ax.bar([i + bar_width for i in x], sector_corr['Dividend Yield'], 
       width=bar_width, label='Dividend Yield', color='#ff7f0e')

ax.set_title('Correlation: Closing Price vs PE Ratio & Dividend Yield by Sector', fontsize=14)
ax.set_xlabel('Sector', fontsize=12)
ax.set_ylabel('Correlation Coefficient', fontsize=12)
ax.set_xticks([i + bar_width/2 for i in x])
ax.set_xticklabels(sector_corr['Sector'], rotation=45, ha='right')
ax.legend()
ax.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("correlation.png")
plt.show()

4. Sector Volume-Trend Correlation¶

In [21]:
print("Unique Trend values:", df['Trend'].unique())
# Map ALL possible categories to numeric values
df['Trend'] = df['Trend'].map({
    'Bullish': 1,
    'Bearish': -1,
    'Stable': 0,
    # Add any other variants if found (e.g., 'stable' → 0)
}).astype(float)  # Force conversion to numeric type

# Handle NaN values (if any unexpected categories exist)
df['Trend'] = df['Trend'].fillna(0)  # Replace NaNs with 0 or drop them
print(df[['Volume', 'Trend']].dtypes)
# Calculate correlation per sector (after fixing data)
volume_trend_corr = (
    df.groupby('Sector')[['Volume', 'Trend']]
    .corr(method='pearson')  # Explicitly use Pearson
    .unstack()
    .iloc[:, 1]  # Select Trend correlation
    .reset_index(name='Correlation')
    .dropna()  # Drop sectors with missing data
)

# Horizontal Bar Chart
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.barh(volume_trend_corr['Sector'], volume_trend_corr['Correlation'], color='teal')
plt.title('Volume-Trend Correlation by Sector')
plt.xlabel('Correlation Coefficient')
plt.ylabel('Sector')
plt.grid(axis='x', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("correlation by sector.png")
plt.show()

10. Sentiment Score vs Price Reversals¶

In [41]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Ensure Price_Reversal is categorical (0 or 1)
df['Price_Reversal'] = np.where(df['Close'].shift(1) > df['Open'], 1, 0)

# Split Sentiment Scores by Price_Reversal groups
reversal_0 = df[df['Price_Reversal'] == 0]['Sentiment_Score']
reversal_1 = df[df['Price_Reversal'] == 1]['Sentiment_Score']

# Create figure and axes explicitly
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))

# Plot boxplots with updated parameter name
box = ax.boxplot(
    [reversal_0, reversal_1],
    tick_labels=['No Reversal (0)', 'Reversal (1)'],  # Changed "labels" to "tick_labels"
    patch_artist=True,
    widths=0.6,
    showmeans=True,
    meanline=True,
    medianprops={'color': 'black'},
    meanprops={'color': 'red', 'linestyle': '--'}
)

# Customize colors
colors = ['lightblue', 'lightgreen']
for patch, color in zip(box['boxes'], colors):
    patch.set_facecolor(color)

# Add labels and title
ax.set_title('Sentiment Score Distribution by Price Reversal', fontsize=14)
ax.set_xlabel('Price Reversal', fontsize=12)
ax.set_ylabel('Sentiment Score', fontsize=12)
ax.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.tight_layout
plt.savefig("sentiment by price.png")
plt.show()

12. OHLC Patterns for Trend Prediction¶

In [60]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Reload the dataset to restore the original structure
df = pd.read_csv(r"synthetic_stock_data.csv")

# Check if 'Date' exists as a column
if 'Date' not in df.columns:
    # If 'Date' was previously set as the index, reset it
    df = df.reset_index().rename(columns={'index': 'Date'})

# Convert 'Date' to datetime and set as index
df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'])
df.set_index('Date', inplace=True)

# Verify data structure
print("Columns after fix:", df.columns)
print("\nFirst 5 rows:\n", df.head())
# Plot OHLC data for the first 30 days
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

# Use explicit axes and ensure data is valid
ax = plt.gca()  # Get current axes
df[['Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Close']].iloc[:30].plot(ax=ax)

# Customize plot
plt.title('OHLC Price Patterns (First 30 Days)', fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('Date', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Price', fontsize=12)
plt.grid(linestyle='--', alpha=0.6)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("ohlc.png")
plt.show()

14. Market Cap Growth Patterns¶

In [6]:
import pandas as pd  # Import pandas to load the DataFrame
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt  # Import matplotlib for plotting

# Load the DataFrame (replace with your actual file path)
df = pd.read_csv(r"synthetic_stock_data.csv")

# Ensure 'Date' is a datetime column and set as index
df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'])
df.set_index('Date', inplace=True)

# Plot the 7-day rolling average of Market Cap
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
df.groupby('Date')['Market_Cap'].mean().rolling(7).mean().plot(color='navy')
plt.title('7-Day Rolling Average Market Cap', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Market Cap', fontsize=12)
plt.xlabel('Date', fontsize=12)
plt.grid(linestyle='--', alpha=0.6)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("market cap.png")
plt.show()

# Deviation from sector median
sector_pe = df.groupby('Sector')['PE_Ratio'].median()
df['PE_Deviation'] = (df['PE_Ratio'] - df['Sector'].map(sector_pe)) / df['Sector'].map(sector_pe)

# Histogram
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.hist(df['PE_Deviation'], bins=30, color='orange', edgecolor='black')
plt.title('PE Ratio Deviation from Sector Median')
